Question 2

# Remove stop words
data("stop_words")

tokens_clean <- pubmed |>
  unnest_tokens(word, abstract) |>
  anti_join(stop_words, by = "word")

# Count what most frequent tokens appear
token_count_clean <- tokens_clean |> 
  count(term, word, sort = TRUE)

# 5 most common tokens for each search term after removing stop words
top5_clean <- token_count_clean |>
  group_by(term) |>
  slice_max(order_by = n, n = 5)

top5_clean |>
  kable(col.names = c("Term", "Word", "Count"),
        caption = "Top 5 Most Common Tokens (After Removing Stop Words)")

These tokens more accurately represent the thematic focus of each group of abstracts.

However, there are a few words used in scientific writing (âpatients withâ and âof covidâ) that showed up on the bar plot which does help in narrowing the domain the abstracts are associated with.

Question 4

# Calculate the TF-IDF value for each word-search term combination
tfidf <- tokens_clean |>
  count(term, word, sort = TRUE) |>
  bind_tf_idf(word, term, n) |>
  arrange(desc(tf_idf))

# 5 tokens from each search term with the highest TF-IDF value
top5_tfidf <- tfidf |>
  group_by(term) |>
  slice_max(order_by = tf_idf, n = 5) |>
  ungroup()

top5_tfidf |> 
  kable(col.names = c("Term", "Word", "Count", "TF", "IDF", "TF-IDF"),

Observations: The results are clearly different from the answers in Question 1. In Question 1, the most frequent words were more general while the TF-IDF emphasizes more topic-specific terminology that is unique to each search term. For instance, âsarsâ and âcovidâ were uniquely associated with covid-related abstracts, while âsweatâ and âfibrosisâ are distinctive in cystic fibrosis abstracts. This demonstrates that TF-IDF is more effective at isolating the terminology that characterizes each search term rather than words that are common across all medical abstracts.

Sentiment Analysis

Question 5

# Sentiment analysis using the NRC lexicon
nrc <- get_sentiments("nrc")

sentiment_count <- tokens_clean |>
  inner_join(nrc) |>
  count(term, sentiment, sort = TRUE)

# Most common sentiment for each search term
top_sentiments <- sentiment_count |>
  group_by(term) |>
  slice_max(order_by = n, n = 1) |>
  ungroup()

top_sentiments |>
  kable(col.names = c("Term", "Sentiment", "Count"),
        caption = "Most Common Sentiment Per Search Term")
Most Common Sentiment Per Search Term

After performing a sentiment analysis using the NRC lexicon, the most common sentiment for each search term are as follows:

  • covid: positive
  • cystic fibrosis: positive
  • meningitis: negative
  • preeclampsia: positive
  • prostate cancer: negative
# Remove "positive" and "negative" from the list
sentiment_count |>

When removing âpositiveâ and ânegativeâ from the list, the most common sentiment changes to more specific emotions:

  • covid: fear
  • cystic fibrosis: disgust
  • meningitis: fear
  • preeclampsia: anticipation
  • prostate cancer: fear

It is interesting to note that after removing âpositiveâ and ânegativeâ, the sentiment for all of the search terms are more negative-sounding even though a few terms like covid, cystic fibrosis, and preeclampsia originally had âpositiveâ as the most common sentiment. Therefore, excluding âpositiveâ and ânegativeâ suggests a better emotional framing of each search term.

Question 6

# Sentiment analysis using AFINN lexicon
afinn <- get_sentiments("afinn")

afinn_sentiment <- pubmed |>
  mutate(abstract_id = row_number()) |>
  unnest_tokens(word, abstract) |>
  anti_join(stop_words, by = "word") |>
  inner_join(afinn) |>
  group_by(term, abstract_id) |>
  summarise(mean_sentiment = mean(value, na.rm = TRUE), .groups = "drop")
# Visualization
afinn_sentiment |>
  ggplot(aes(x = term, y = mean_sentiment, fill = term)) +
  geom_violin(trim = FALSE, alpha = 0.7, show.legend = FALSE) +
  geom_boxplot(width = 0.1, color = "black", alpha = 0.6, outlier.shape = NA) +
  labs(title = "Sentiment Distribution per Search Term",
       x = "Search Term",
       y = "Average Sentiment Score") +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 13)
afinn_sentiment |>
  group_by(term) |>
  summarise(avg_sentiment = mean(mean_sentiment, na.rm = TRUE)) |>
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(term, avg_sentiment), y = avg_sentiment, fill = term)) +
  geom_col(show.legend = FALSE) +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(title = "Average Sentiment Scores per Search Term",
       x = "Search Term",
       y = "Average Sentiment Score") +
  theme_minimal()

Interpretation: After performing a sentiment analysis using the AFINN lexicon to get an average score for each abstract, the only term that had a positive score is cystic fibrosis while all the other search terms had negative sentiment scores. This is clearly noticeable in the bar plot but also in the violin plot, with the distribution for cystic fibrosis being wider towards the top. Meanwhile, the width of the other search terms are mostly the widest at values below 0, meaning their abstracts are more negative.

Back in Question 5, the most common sentiment from the NRC lexicon for cystic fibrosis was âpositiveâ. After removing âpositiveâ from the list, the most common sentiment for it was âdisgustâ. Given the outputs from Question 5, it arguably makes sense for cystic fibrosis to not be as negative compared to the other diseases. When looking up this disorder, the symptoms include persistent cough with thick mucus, wheezing, frequent lung infections, abdominal pain, sweat that tastes salty, and salty skin which can give off a âdisgustâ sentiment. Therefore, this disorder, compared to the other ones, is arguably less severe, which explains why it is the only search term with a positive sentiment score.
